The paper deals with distributed graph algorithms, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The main problem being addressed is graph coloring, which is a fundamental problem in graph theory and falls under the category of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the concept of arboricity, which is a measure of sparsity, and this falls under the category of Networked Systems (cs.NI). The algorithms presented in the paper involve randomized techniques, which falls under the category of Algorithms (cs.AL). Finally, the paper also discusses the lower bounds for distributed graph coloring, which falls under the category of Discrete Mathematics (cs.GT).
